vibe: 2.0

meta:
  name: vibe_v2_stdlib_refactor
  description: >
    Standard library transformation plan. Defines what to delete, adapt,
    and create in vibe/stdlib/ for the v2 pivot.
  session_id: 2026-03-10-a7f3b2
  created_at: "2026-03-10"
  author: claude
  tags:
    - stdlib
    - migration
    - v2
  status: draft

imports:
  - plans/10_format_spec.vibe

context:
  problem: |
    The v1 standard library contains five modules, most of which support
    runtime execution (tools.vibe, plan_manifest_schema.vibe, gates.vibe).
    The v2 stdlib needs to provide document templates, quality criteria
    libraries, and reusable context blocks instead.

  constraints: |
    - Must not break the repo structure (stdlib stays under vibe/stdlib/)
    - Templates must be valid v2 .vibe files that serve as starting points
    - Quality criteria should be importable and composable
    - Keep context_budget.vibe concepts (useful for AI context management)

  assumptions: |
    - AI systems will import stdlib templates to bootstrap new documents
    - Quality criteria libraries reduce boilerplate in plan files
    - The stdlib is small enough to manage without a package system

  scope: |
    Covers vibe/stdlib/ changes only. Spec document changes are in
    70_spec_rewrites.vibe. Schema changes are in 10_format_spec.vibe.

artifacts:
  - path: vibe/stdlib/tools.vibe
    kind: vibe
    description: v1 tool definitions module -- to be deleted
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - File is removed from repository
      - No remaining imports reference this file

  - path: vibe/stdlib/plan_manifest_schema.vibe
    kind: vibe
    description: v1 plan manifest schema wiring -- to be deleted
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - File is removed from repository
      - No remaining imports reference this file

  - path: vibe/stdlib/schemas/plan_manifest.schema.json
    kind: json
    description: v1 plan manifest JSON schema -- to be deleted
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - File and directory removed from repository

  - path: vibe/stdlib/quality.vibe
    kind: vibe
    description: v2 quality criteria library (replaces validators.vibe)
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Valid v2 .vibe file
      - Contains reusable quality criteria for common checks
      - Importable by other .vibe files

  - path: vibe/stdlib/templates/overview.vibe
    kind: vibe
    description: Template for overview documents
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Valid v2 .vibe file with placeholder content
      - Follows overview archetype from 20_document_types.vibe

  - path: vibe/stdlib/templates/architecture.vibe
    kind: vibe
    description: Template for architecture documents
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Valid v2 .vibe file with placeholder content
      - Follows architecture archetype

  - path: vibe/stdlib/templates/implementation_plan.vibe
    kind: vibe
    description: Template for implementation plan documents
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Valid v2 .vibe file with placeholder content
      - Follows implementation plan archetype

  - path: vibe/stdlib/templates/risk_assessment.vibe
    kind: vibe
    description: Template for risk assessment documents
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Valid v2 .vibe file with placeholder content
      - Follows risk assessment archetype

  - path: vibe/stdlib/templates/adr_collection.vibe
    kind: vibe
    description: Template for ADR collection documents
    status: planned
    acceptance_criteria:
      - Valid v2 .vibe file with placeholder content
      - Follows ADR collection archetype

sections:
  - id: delete_plan
    type: checklist
    title: Files to Delete
    content: |
      The following stdlib files exist solely to support v1 runtime execution
      and have no equivalent in v2:

      - [ ] vibe/stdlib/tools.vibe
            Defines fs.read, fs.write, fs.list, fs.apply_patch, exec.run.
            Reason: Tool definitions are an execution concern. The tools
            available depend on the runtime, not the plan format.

      - [ ] vibe/stdlib/plan_manifest_schema.vibe
            Wires plan_manifest.schema.json validation.
            Reason: Plan manifests are a v1 execution artifact. v2 does
            not produce or consume plan manifests.

      - [ ] vibe/stdlib/schemas/plan_manifest.schema.json
            JSON schema for the plan manifest format.
            Reason: Same as above. No plan manifests in v2.

  - id: adapt_plan
    type: design
    title: Files to Adapt
    content: |
      ### gates.vibe -> quality_gates.vibe (or merge into quality.vibe)
      Current: Defines gate types (file_exists, file_tree, json_schema,
      content_rules, command_success, diff_budget) for runtime execution.
      Adapted: Remove execution gate semantics. Keep quality gate concepts
      as quality criteria patterns. For example:
      - file_exists gate -> "required artifact exists" quality criterion
      - json_schema gate -> "artifact validates against schema" criterion
      - content_rules gate -> "content meets standards" criterion
      Decision: Merge into quality.vibe rather than keeping separate file.

      ### validators.vibe -> quality.vibe
      Current: Defines json_parse, file_tree, content_rules, diff_budget
      validators that a runtime executes after workflow completion.
      Adapted: Convert to importable quality criteria. Instead of executable
      validators, provide quality criterion templates that documents can
      import and reference in their quality section.

      ### context_budget.vibe
      Current: Context budgeting and compaction guidance for long-running
      agent workflows.
      Adapted: Still relevant for AI systems working with .vibe files.
      Update version to 2.0, remove references to runtime steps and plan
      manifests, keep context window management guidance.

  - id: create_plan
    type: design
    title: New Files to Create
    content: |
      ### vibe/stdlib/quality.vibe
      Importable quality criteria library. Provides reusable quality
      criterion definitions that documents can reference:

        quality:
          - id: stdlib_artifacts_exist
            type: checklist
            description: All planned artifacts have been created
            criteria: |
              Every artifact listed in the artifacts section exists at
              its specified path.

          - id: stdlib_yaml_valid
            type: test
            description: Document is valid YAML
            criteria: |
              The .vibe file parses without YAML syntax errors.

          - id: stdlib_schema_valid
            type: test
            description: Document validates against v2 schema
            criteria: |
              The .vibe file passes validation against
              vibe/schema/vibe.schema.json.

          - id: stdlib_sections_complete
            type: review
            description: All sections have substantive content
            criteria: |
              No section has empty or placeholder-only content.

      ### vibe/stdlib/templates/
      Five templates matching the document archetypes defined in
      20_document_types.vibe. Each template is a valid v2 .vibe file
      with skeleton structure and placeholder content that AI systems
      can fill in:

      - overview.vibe: Problem, users, approach, risks, success criteria
      - architecture.vibe: Current state, design, data model, API, risks
      - implementation_plan.vibe: Scope, approach, artifacts, tasks, verification
      - risk_assessment.vibe: Context, risks, mitigations, monitoring
      - adr_collection.vibe: Background context + decisions array

  - id: migration_order
    type: checklist
    title: Migration Execution Order
    content: |
      1. [ ] Create vibe/stdlib/templates/ directory
      2. [ ] Create quality.vibe (new file, no dependencies)
      3. [ ] Create all five template files
      4. [ ] Update context_budget.vibe to v2 format
      5. [ ] Delete tools.vibe
      6. [ ] Delete plan_manifest_schema.vibe
      7. [ ] Delete schemas/plan_manifest.schema.json
      8. [ ] Rename or delete gates.vibe (content merged into quality.vibe)
      9. [ ] Delete or archive validators.vibe (replaced by quality.vibe)
      10. [ ] Update all imports in project.vibe and other files

decisions:
  - id: dec_merge_gates_validators
    title: Merge gates.vibe and validators.vibe into single quality.vibe
    status: proposed
    context: |
      v1 has separate concepts for gates (pre-conditions checked during
      execution) and validators (post-conditions checked after execution).
      In v2 without execution, both are quality criteria.
    options:
      - name: keep_separate
        description: Adapt gates.vibe and validators.vibe as separate v2 files
      - name: merge_into_quality
        description: Combine both into a single quality.vibe
    chosen: merge_into_quality
    rationale: |
      Without execution semantics, the distinction between pre-conditions
      and post-conditions disappears. Both become "criteria for evaluating
      the plan/output." A single file is simpler and avoids artificial
      separation.
    consequences:
      - One file to maintain instead of two
      - gates.vibe and validators.vibe both get deleted
      - Quality criteria are more general (not tied to execution phases)

  - id: dec_template_format
    title: Templates are valid .vibe files with placeholders
    status: proposed
    context: |
      Templates could be separate formats (e.g., mustache templates,
      JSON schema generators) or valid .vibe files with placeholder
      content.
    options:
      - name: template_engine
        description: Use a template engine with variables and conditionals
      - name: valid_vibe_files
        description: Templates are valid .vibe files with placeholder strings
    chosen: valid_vibe_files
    rationale: |
      Valid .vibe files are self-documenting, require no template engine,
      and can be used directly as starting points. AI systems are good
      at replacing placeholder content. A template engine adds complexity
      for minimal benefit.
    consequences:
      - Templates parse as valid YAML and valid v2 .vibe
      - Placeholders use descriptive strings like "[Describe the problem]"
      - No template engine dependency

quality:
  - id: q_delete_safe
    type: checklist
    description: Deletions don't break remaining files
    criteria: |
      - No remaining .vibe file imports a deleted module
      - No spec document references a deleted module without noting removal
      - project.vibe imports are updated

  - id: q_quality_importable
    type: test
    description: quality.vibe is usable via imports
    criteria: |
      - quality.vibe is a valid v2 .vibe file
      - Other .vibe files can import it and reference its quality criteria
      - Quality criteria IDs are namespaced (stdlib_ prefix)

  - id: q_templates_valid
    type: test
    description: All templates are valid v2 .vibe files
    criteria: |
      - Each template parses as valid YAML
      - Each template has vibe: 2.0 header
      - Each template has all required fields populated
      - Each template follows its corresponding archetype
